 To create a new page per figure in LaTeX, you can use the `\clearpage` command before each figure. Here's how to do it:

```latex
\begin{document}
% First content...

\clearpage
\begin{figure}[p]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{figure1.png}
  \caption{First figure}
  \label{fig:figure1}
\end{figure}

\clearpage
\begin{figure}[p]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{figure2.png}
  \caption{Second figure}
  \label{fig:figure2}
\end{figure}

% Rest of the document...
\end{document}
```

The `\clearpage` command forces LaTeX to output all pending floats and starts a new page. Using the `[p]` placement specifier for the figure environment tells LaTeX that this figure should take up a full page.

Alternatively, if you want to automate this for all figures in your document, you can add this to your preamble:

```latex
\usepackage{float}
\floatplacement{figure}{p}
```

This will make all figures default to page float placement, though it doesn't guarantee each will be on a separate page if multiple small figures can fit on one page.

