 Looking at your LaTeX code, I see what's causing the uneven vertical spacing. The issue is with how you're using the `\vspace` command in combination with the line breaks (`\\`).

Here's how to fix it:

```latex
\clearpage
\begin{figure}
\begin{minipage}{0.3\textwidth}
    \centering
    \threedaxes[2]{\{i, t_i\}}{2}{\{t_i, i\}}{2}{\{\tau\}(\pm\pm\mp)^*}{0}
\end{minipage}

\vspace{1cm}

\begin{minipage}{0.3\textwidth}
    \centering
    \threedaxes[2]{\{t_i, i\}}{2}{\{t_j, j\}}{2}{\{k\}(\mp++)^*}{0}
\end{minipage}

\vspace{1cm}

\begin{minipage}{0.3\textwidth}
    \centering
    \threedaxes[2]{\{t_i, i\}}{2}{\{j, t_j\}}{2}{\{t_k\}(+\mp\pm)^*}{0}
\end{minipage}
\end{figure}
```

The key changes I made:

1. Removed the line breaks (`\\`) that appeared right before each `\vspace` command
2. Added blank lines between each minipage environment for clarity

The problem in your original code was that the `\\` at the end of each minipage followed immediately by `\vspace` can cause inconsistent spacing. By removing the line breaks and letting the minipage environments stand alone with the `\vspace` commands between them, you should get more consistent vertical spacing between your graphs.

